---

# State Machine

Every research project exists in one state.

```
Knowledge Collection

↓

Landscape Modeling

↓

Gap Discovery

↓

Hypothesis Building

↓

Idea Generation

↓

Idea Evaluation

↓

Experiment Design

↓

Experiment Running

↓

Evidence Collection

↓

Reviewer Simulation

↓

Decision

↓

Knowledge Update

↓

Repeat
```

A project can move forward or backward.

Research is not linear.

---

# Memory Kernel

The Memory Kernel maintains long-term memory.

It stores

- Papers
- Concepts
- Ideas
- Experiments
- Failures
- Reviewer comments
- Decisions
- Lessons learned
- Research history

Nothing should be regenerated if it already exists.

---

# World Model

The World Model represents the current understanding of a research field.

It contains

## Problem Space

Known research problems.

---

## Solution Space

Existing methods.

---

## Assumption Space

Assumptions behind existing methods.

---

## Failure Space

Known failure cases.

---

## Evidence Space

Evidence supporting current beliefs.

---

## Unknown Space

Questions that remain unanswered.

---

Every node stores

- Confidence
- Supporting Evidence
- Contradicting Evidence
- Last Updated
- Source

The World Model evolves after every iteration.

---

# Reasoning Engine

Responsibilities

- Analyze literature
- Detect assumptions
- Discover contradictions
- Explain failures
- Infer root causes
- Update beliefs

Output

- Problems
- Gaps
- Root Causes
- Hypotheses

---

# Planning Engine

Responsibilities

Select the next best action.

Possible actions

- Read more papers
- Generate ideas
- Design experiments
- Run validation
- Analyze failures
- Simplify methods
- Pivot direction
- Prepare submission

Planning is based on current state.

---

# Execution Engine

Executes research tasks.

Examples

- Literature review
- Idea generation
- Experiment planning
- Code generation
- Data analysis
- Visualization
- Ablation study
- Benchmark evaluation

Execution never changes the World Model directly.

Only evidence does.

---

# Evaluation Engine

Evaluates every research artifact.

Evaluation dimensions

## Novelty

## Importance

## Technical Quality

## Evidence Quality

## Reproducibility

## Scalability

## Practical Value

## Scientific Value

## Risk

## Confidence

Output

Research Score

---

# Reviewer Engine

Simulate reviewers.

Questions

- Is the contribution novel?
- Is the evidence sufficient?
- Is the comparison fair?
- What assumptions are hidden?
- Is the claim overstated?
- What experiments are missing?
- Would this survive rebuttal?

Output

Weakness Report

Acceptance Probability

Improvement Suggestions

---

# Scheduler

The Scheduler determines what should happen next.

Instead of fixed workflows.

Decision examples

IF

Gap confidence is low

THEN

Read more literature

---

IF

Hypothesis confidence is high

THEN

Generate ideas

---

IF

Experiment contradicts hypothesis

THEN

Update World Model

Generate new hypothesis

---

IF

Evidence is sufficient

THEN

Run reviewer simulation

---

IF

Reviewer score is acceptable

THEN

Prepare submission

---

The Scheduler makes Research OS adaptive.

---

# Confidence System

Every object stores confidence.

```
0.0

↓

Unknown

↓

0.3

↓

Weak Evidence

↓

0.6

↓

Likely

↓

0.8

↓

Strong Evidence

↓

1.0

↓

Verified
```

Confidence changes after every experiment.

Nothing is permanently true.

---

# Research Loop

```
Observe

↓

Collect Knowledge

↓

Update World Model

↓

Generate Questions

↓

Discover Gaps

↓

Analyze Root Causes

↓

Generate Hypotheses

↓

Generate Ideas

↓

Evaluate Ideas

↓

Plan Experiments

↓

Collect Evidence

↓

Reviewer Simulation

↓

Decision

↓

Update Memory

↓

Update World Model

↓

Repeat
```

Research continuously improves the World Model.

---

# Research Objectives

Research contributions may include

- New Problems
- New Insights
- New Theories
- New Algorithms
- New Architectures
- New Training Strategies
- New Optimization Methods
- New Inference Methods
- New Benchmarks
- New Datasets
- New Evaluation Metrics
- New Systems
- New Applications

The operating system is domain-independent.

---

# Mission Statement

Research OS 2.0 is a state-driven, evidence-based, self-evolving cognitive operating system.

Its mission is not to maximize publications.

Its mission is to maximize understanding.

Better understanding produces better questions.

Better questions produce better research.

Better research produces meaningful scientific progress.
